                   </image>                    </fig>                            </li>            <li id="li_N10062_N1002C_N1001C_N10001" >                <p >Type a name for the memory profile.</p>            </li>            <li id="li_N1006B_N1002C_N1001C_N10001" >                <p >Click <uicontrol >Create Memory                        Profile</uicontrol> to save the profile and close the dialog box.</p>            </li>        </ol>            <p >You can apply this profile to other hosts by editing the host                settings in the web administration interface. For information about editing a host,                see <xref href="jow1404333790046.xml" />. You can also use the                following CLI command to apply a memory profile to a host:</p>            <codeblock ><systemoutput >~(keystone-admin)$ </systemoutput><userinput >system host-apply-memprofile <varname >memoryprofile</varname> <varname >hostid</varname></userinput></codeblock>            <p >where <varname >memoryprofile</varname> is the name or UUID of the memory profile, and                    <varname >hostid</varname> is the name or UUID of the host.</p>            <p >To manage memory profiles, you can use the <wintitle >Memory Profiles</wintitle> tab                on the <wintitle >System Inventory</wintitle> page, or you can use the following CLI                commands:</p>            <ul id="ul_x1x_plr_5r">                <li >                    <p >To list memory profiles:</p>                    <codeblock ><systemoutput >~(keystone-admin)$ </systemoutput><userinput >system memprofile-list</userinput></codeblock>                </li>                <li >                    <p >To show details for a memory profile:</p>                    <codeblock ><systemoutput >~(keystone-admin)$ </systemoutput><userinput >system memprofile-show <varname >memoryprofile</varname></userinput></codeblock>                    <p >where <varname >memoryprofile</varname> is the name or UUID of the memory                        profile.</p>                </li>                <li >                    <p >To delete a memory profile:</p>                    <codeblock ><systemoutput >~(keystone-admin)$ </systemoutput><userinput >system memprofile-delete <varname >memoryprofile</varname></userinput></codeblock>                    <p >where <varname >memoryprofile</varname> is the name or UUID of the memory                        profile.</p>                </li>            </ul>            </body></topic>